al name from Lindsey in Lincolnshire, England. This is first found in the form <i>Lindissi</i>, apparently a derivative of the British name of   Lincoln  . To this was later added the Old English element <i>ēg</i> ‘island’, since the place was virtually cut off by the surrounding fenland. The surname was taken to Scotland at an early date and is the name of an important and powerful Scottish family.","Irish: adopted as an equivalent ofvarious Gaelic names (see   Lindsey  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Linzy","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish, Irish, or English   Lindsay   or   Lindsey  . Compare   Lenzy  ."]},{"name":"Linzey","meanings":["English: variant of   Lindsay   or   Lindsey  ."]},{"name":"Lindsey","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lindsay  .","Irish: shortened and Anglicized form of various Gaelic surnames, as for example <b>Ó Loingsigh</b> (see   Lynch   1), <b>Mac Giolla Fhionntóg</b> (see   McClintock  ), and <b>Ó Fhloinn</b> (see   Flynn   and   Lynn  )."]},{"name":"Lincoln","meanings":["English: habitational name from the city of Lincoln, so named from an original British name <i>Lindo-</i> ‘lake’ + Latin <i>colonia</i> ‘settlement, colony’. The place was an important administrative center during the Roman occupation of Britain and in the Middle Ages it was a center for the manufacture of cloth, including the famous ‘Lincoln green’.","African American: adoption of the surname in 1 above, in honor of Abraham Lincoln, the 16th president of the US, who abolished slavery.","History: Abraham Lincoln (1809–65), 16th president of the US, was the son of an illiterate laborer, descended from Samuel Lincoln, who had emigrated from England to MA in 1637."]},{"name":"Linsey","meanings":["Scottish, Irish, or English: variant of   Lindsay   or   Lindsey  .","Americanized form of German   Linse   or Swiss German <b>Linsi</b>, see   Lins  ."]}]},{"name":"Baldric","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Baldry  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Baldry","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): from the Middle English personal names <i>Baldri(c)</i> and <i>Baldrich</i>. The first is usually from ancient Germanic <i>Baldric</i>, which was common in the French forms <i>Baldri</i> and <i>Baudri</i>. The second represents the cognate Old English name <i>Bealdrīc</i>, formed from <i>beald</i> ‘bold, brave’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘ruler’, which is attested in Middle English forms such as <i>Belrich</i>, <i>Balrich</i>, <i>Baltriht</i>, and <i>Baldrich</i>."]}]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":2,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":22,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":32,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large